Section 1:
1 L.D. 169
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 102, L.D. 169, “An Act to Amend the
10 Laws Regarding Estate Recovery and Planning for Long-term Care”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, Establishing the Commission to Study MaineCare Estate Recovery'
13 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
14 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
15 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
16 Whereas, this legislation establishes the Commission to Study MaineCare Estate
17 Recovery; and
18 Whereas, this legislation must take effect before the expiration of the 90-day period
19 so that the commission may meet in a timely manner and make its report to the Legislature;
20 and
21 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
22 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
23 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
24 therefore, be it
25 Sec. 1. Commission established. Resolved: That the Commission to Study
26 MaineCare Estate Recovery, referred to in this resolve as "the commission," is established.
27 Sec. 2. Commission membership. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint Rule
28 353, the commission consists of 10 members as follows:
29 1. Four members appointed by the President of the Senate, including:
30 A. Two members of the Senate, including a member from each of the 2 parties holding
31 the largest number of seats in the Legislature;
32 B. One member representing an organization that advocates for the rights of elderly
33 individuals; and
Page 1 - 132LR0275(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 102, L.D. 169
1 C. One member who is an attorney who specializes in long-term care planning;
2 2. Four members appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives, including:
3 A. Two members of the House of Representatives, including a member from each of
4 the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats in the Legislature;
5 B. One member who is an individual with lived experience navigating the MaineCare
6 estate recovery procedures; and
7 C. One member who is an individual representing an organization that advocates for
8 the rights of individuals with disabilities;
9 3. The Commissioner of Health and Human Services or the commissioner's designee;
10 and
11 4. The long-term care ombudsman established pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes,
12 Title 22, section 5106, subsection 11-C or the ombudsman's designee.
13 Sec. 3. Chairs. Resolved: That the first-named Senate member is the Senate chair
14 and the first-named House of Representatives member is the House chair of the
15 commission.
16 Sec. 4. Appointments; convening of commission. Resolved: That all
17 appointments must be made no later than 30 days following the effective date of this
18 resolve. The appointing authorities shall notify the Executive Director of the Legislative
19 Council once all appointments have been completed. After appointment of all members,
20 the chairs shall call and convene the first meeting of the commission. If 30 days or more
21 after the effective date of this resolve a majority of but not all appointments have been
22 made, the chairs may request authority and the Legislative Council may grant authority for
23 the commission to meet and conduct its business.
24 Sec. 5. Duties. Resolved: That the commission shall study issues associated with
25 the MaineCare estate recovery procedures, including:
26 1. A review of the history of the MaineCare estate recovery procedures and review of
27 the reasons behind the establishment of the procedures as they exist currently;
28 2. An examination of allowable flexibilities in the administration of Medicaid estate
29 recovery procedures, including any possible Medicaid waivers;
30 3. A review of estate recovery models employed by other states; and
31 4. An examination of best practices and innovations in Medicaid estate recovery.
32 The commission shall develop recommendations for reforms to the MaineCare estate
33 recovery procedures.
34 Sec. 6. Staff assistance. Resolved: That the Legislative Council shall provide
35 necessary staffing services to the commission, except that Legislative Council staff support
36 is not authorized when the Legislature is in regular or special session.
37 Sec. 7. Report. Resolved: That, no later than December 3, 2025, the commission
38 shall submit a report that includes its findings and recommendations, including suggested
39 legislation, to the Joint Standing Committee on Health and Human Services. The
40 committee may introduce legislation related to the report of the commission to the Second
41 Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
Page 2 - 132LR0275(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 102, L.D. 169
1 Emergency clause. In view of the emergency cited in the preamble, this legislation
2 takes effect when approved.'
3 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
4 number to read consecutively.
5 SUMMARY
66 This amendment replaces the bill with a resolve. The amendment creates the
77 Commission to Study MaineCare Estate Recovery. The commission is tasked with
88 studying issues associated with the MaineCare estate recovery procedures, including a
99 review of the history of the MaineCare estate recovery procedures and review of the reasons
1100 behind the establishment of the procedures as they exist currently; an examination of
1111 allowable flexibilities in the administration of Medicaid estate recovery procedures,
1122 including any possible Medicaid waivers; a review of estate recovery models employed by
1133 other states; and an examination of best practices and innovations in Medicaid estate
1144 recovery. The commission must submit a report by December 3, 2025 to the Joint Standing
1155 Committee on Health and Human Services. The committee may present legislation related
1166 to the report of the commission to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
1177 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
1188 (See attached)
Page 3 - 132LR0275(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
